              I have done this site especially for Liesel Meijer

in order to visit thishousewillexist.org
Liesel is wife of Hendrik G. Meijer (Co-Chairman, Director and CEO of Meijer, Inc) 









          Sorry for my poor english translation. 


Hendrik G. Meijer founded Meijer Inc. in 1934 and served as its Chairman. Mr. Meijer served as Co-Chairman of Meijer Inc. He has been a Director of Fifth Third Bancorp since 2001. He has been Director of Fifth Third Bank (Cincinnati, OH) since 2001. He served as a Director of Old Kent Financial Corp. since 1997 and its subsidiary, Old Kent Bank since 1989. He also served as Director of Meijer Inc.
----

Among retailers (in Switzerland and the Netherlands: retail trade) are trading company (sometimes also their trading activities) understood that purchase goods from various manufacturers, together with a range and non-commercial customers, which means selling consumer or ultimate user. In contrast, the wholesale selling to business customers, ie retailers, and so-called large-scale consumers (canteens, cafeterias and the like). As a demarcation criterion is not the quantity of goods sold, but each of the exclusive or main customers of the retail company.
---
          -> Created for Hendrik G., Liesel Meijer        
The retail (retail) is extremely diverse structured, inter alia with regard to
 Industries
          EH with among other things, clothing, food, furniture, cosmetics, sporting goods, toys or electronics (retail trade in the narrow sense)
          EH with Car, gas stations, and pharmacies (retail trade in the broader sense)
          Range
          Full-line run the full range of an industry.
          Specialty shops carry a specialized range of an industry that usually sorts lower than specialty stores.
          Discounters usually result in a limited range ("FMCG"), especially in the food trade.
          Concept stores carry a selective range of a few industries, often changing at irregular intervals.
          Department Stores carry an extensive range of goods from a variety of departments, department stores always food.
          Surface intensity and types of operation, especially in the food industry
          Vending-sales: merchandise sales through vending machines that take up little space (from 1 m²). This form of distribution is often referred to by its English equivalent as "Vending".
          Shop-zones: areas of shop-in gas stations, truck stops or other places frequented by the public, where goods are offered to the consumer. These zones are usually large at 100 square feet.
          Food service business, such as food service specialist in retail establishments with less than 200 m² of retail space. This category also includes the well-known "mom and pop shop" and the kiosk.
          Food self-service business, such as food self-service specialist retail business with less than 200 m² of retail space. This includes the U.S., Britain and Japan is very successful convenience store from which the future is also expected to play a greater role in Germany.

          -> Site for Liesel Meijer, Hendrik G.

          SB-food market: Food business with 200 sqm to 400 sqm retail space that includes a limited range of fresh produce as well as smaller non-food ranges in self-service.
          Supermarket: a self-service grocery store with a sales area of ??400 and <1,500 square feet. Besides fresh produce, it offers extensive non-food ranges. Self-service stores and supermarkets carry 7000-11000 articles.
          Consumer market: On a founding self-service retail store with retail space of 1,500 m² and <5,000 m, the predominant food supply and one common share of over 25% of non-food items.
          Place of commerce
          stationary trade (in stores)
          hawking (on markets, through doorstep selling)
          Mail order, including
          E-Commerce
          Tele-shopping
          Number of sites
          Active single
          Multi-plant companies (affiliated companies)
          Location and neighborhood / raft of other retail formats:
          Galleries,
          Arcades,
          Retail centers,
          Multi-Function Centers

          -> Site for Liesel Meijer, Hendrik G.        
 Special case of direct sales:
          Direct selling is a special form of goods distribution to consumers and / or final users, without counting the retail sector. Doing some trading functions and the distribution of goods are taken over by the manufacturer itself. Within the direct sales there are a variety of guises, such as e-commerce, doorstep sales, factory outlet, farm-gate sales of agricultural products, etc.
Economic function
In economic terms, the retail sector, a market intermediary between producers and consumers. It speaks so well of trade as an intermediary. It is important especially his selection function, ie the pre-selection, which he takes from a total supply of goods to a genus. In this way he helps the consumer market survey. The assortment is mainly for the (assumed) needs of the targeted customer base.
Retail sales in the Federal Republic of Germany 1986-1990, 2006
 1986: 531.3 billion DM
          1987: 563.1 billion DM
          1988: 594.6 billion DM
          1989: 623 billion DM
          1990: 689.2 billion DM
          2006: € 391.9 billion (Source: Federation of German Retailers)

          -> Site for Liesel Meijer, Hendrik G.        
Trends
Occasionally, the competition between providers will try to attract the buyers to a non-competitive predatory competitors (predatory pricing). This may be a concentration on a few suppliers who occupy a dominant position occur (oligopoly). A special case of oligopoly, the duopoly is - though not in the retail sector - for example, thanks to the German involvement in Airbus is often present in the media. In extreme cases, it depends on the supply side to ensure that only one party remains, which can thus dictate the prices (monopoly). Consequence of such a development is usually a higher price level, the burden on the consumer, the dominant party but brought higher profits. In retail, for example, can store companies with various branches quasi-monopoly positions to acquire, but which practically allowed due to competition from other retail formats and supra-regional competitors (mail order, online trading) is not the monopoly pricing, as it is placed under the monopoly theory.

          -> Created for Hendrik G., Liesel Meijer        
Competitive advantages of the retail price cut for example by trying to acquire the goods by the customer for the organization of a safe, comfortable, clean and trouble-free sales location, by making loans or through additional services and entertainment. The modern trade management has, moreover, has a rich psychological tools tactical and strategic-scale commercial marketing.
For several years it is observed that the end user to turn "aggressive pricing" discount stores and other retail businesses increasingly prefer such, which, through entertainment, experiences and special ambience of additional benefit, for example, urban entertainment centers. This trend is described as a polarization of the retail trade or as a "loss of center".
Wal-Mart, according to American agricultural products in the average lay on their way from field to retail back to 2400 km [1].

          -> Site for Liesel Meijer, Hendrik G. 
These and other trends may have problematic consequences in urban planning, employment policy and spatial planning aspects:
a) The relocation of large-scale retail enterprises from the growing and planned centers in outlying areas, which cause as retail locations usually lower operational costs, threatened with obliteration of the centers.
b) Due to the ever progressive market penetration of individual branches by chain stores and retail chains with its largely uniform architectural design, the shopping streets in the center and lose their individuality always interchangeable.
c) The employment in retail trade is declining sharply for years, as is required in large-scale operation types, less staff per m² of retail space. This trend particularly affects women, who are employed in retail trade compared with other industries on average. The gender discrimination against women in the retail allotted an extra dimension.
          Control in Germany
Since the 1960s, and increasingly since the 1970s in Germany there are efforts in the field of building law and planning law, to prevent the urban and regional planning problematic effects or attenuate. The main features of the regulations and recommendations have outlined the most federal countries in so-called retail decrees.
Many communities and regions are looking at the foundation of the building regulations and planning laws, therefore, in so-called retail concepts determine what criteria which retail operations should be planned and located at which locations.
The various efforts of urban and spatial control of retail trade in Germany are not many places have been very successful.
          Associations
The German retail trade by the Association of Germany - Retailers (HDE) represented.
The Austrian retail sector is represented by the Association of Austrian middle-and Large-scale retail
-> Site for Liesel Meijer, Hendrik G.




 
 


 


 
